stExp:
stakeholder: Brian, instructor for practicing C programming, calculator user (not programmer)

==================================================
Brian: 

Expected reverse-polish calculator:
EB01: numbers are added into stack, when operation is performed on top 2 numbers of stack:
EB02: it supports floating point number format (32 bit is enough);
EB03: it supports minus sign format;  

EB04: supported operations: * + - / % 

EB05: [ENTER] is for updating stack  

CONOPS:
	input: 5 5 6 + [enter]
	stack: 5 11 

	input: 5.1 5 6 + - [enter]
	stack: -5.9 

	input: 1 1 -2.1 + 1 * [enter]
	stack: -3.1 

	input: 1 1 + TOP [ENTER]
	output: 2

EB06: also should support special commands: 

	General:
	CLEAR - for clearing the stack 
	TOP - get top element
	DUP - duplicate top element	
	SWAP - swap top 2 elements
	EXIT - quit the program

	Math:
	SIN - sinus of top number
	COS - cosine of top number
	EXP - e powered by top number
	POW - power operation of top 2 numbers
==================================================
average user:

EU01: When I first enter the program, probably need some manual or help section 
because reverse-polish is not most shared type of calculator

EU02: Program should clearly show how to open that manual section, and 
convenient way of returning back to calculator  

EU03: That hint to how to open help/manual section and quit should stay at any stage of 
calculation 

EU04: fast hint on how to close the program

==================================================
C-instructor:

EC01: I expect to get clear programming, correct use of concepts 
EC02: program should be optimized getting great time performance
EC03: keep code structured and readable


Constraints/Assumptions:

CON-01: implemented in C
CON-02: no dynamic allocation (malloc)

assumptions: user can work with terminal


